                                                                  9234 1451
I. SUMMARY                                                        9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The cross section data file for neutron reactions with 237U    9234 1451
has been reevaluated over the incident neutron energy range from  9234 1451
10-5 eV to 30 MeV.  This work builds upon an earlier Los Alamos   9234 1451
evaluation (Yo94) that featured replacement of all cross section  9234 1451
data above 10 keV with results from a new theoretical analysis.   9234 1451
The present analysis updates the cross sections and continuum     9234 1451
energy-angle distributions with results from a systematic         9234 1451
analysis of 232,233,234,235,236,238U + n reactions.               9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   Details of the present analysis are given in the sections      9234 1451
that follow.  Some general features of the work are:              9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
1.  The ENDF/B-VI n + 237U resonance parameters were adopted at   9234 1451
neutron energies below 10 keV with modification of the fission    9234 1451
channel to better agree with data.  The resonance analysis was    9234 1451
suitably joined with the present analysis at 10 keV.              9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
2.  A systematic analysis was performed of uranium isotopes       9234 1451
between 232U and 238U.  An isospin-dependent coupled-channel      9234 1451
optical model potential was developed for the uranium isotopes    9234 1451
and was used to calculate the n + 237U neutron total cross        9234 1451
section, elastic and inelastic scattering cross sections,         9234 1451
elastic scattering angular distributions, and reaction cross      9234 1451
sections.  Transmission coefficients were obtained from the       9234 1451
optical model for theoretical calculations with reaction theory   9234 1451
codes.                                                            9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
3.  Prompt nubar and the fission neutron spectra were taken from  9234 1451
the existing ENDF/B-VI evaluation.                                9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
4.  Angular distributions of (n,n') reactions were carried over   9234 1451
from the 1994 evaluation (Yo94). Those distributions were         9234 1451
obtained from a similar coupled-channels optical potential.       9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
II.  THEORETICAL ANALYSIS                                         9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
  The basic approach followed was to fit the available            9234 1451
experimental data for (n,f), (n,g), (n,xn), and other reactions   9234 1451
for the stable uranium isotopes using nuclear models, and to      9234 1451
then use reasonable extrapolations of the parameters to infer     9234 1451
cross sections for 237U.  To perform the analysis, we utilized    9234 1451
the Hauser-Feshbach reaction theory code COMNUC, the Hauser-      9234 1451
Feshbach/preequilibrium reaction theory code GNASH, and the       9234 1451
coupled-channels optical model code ECIS.                         9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
    A.  Optical Model                                             9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The deformed optical model potential was obtained by           9234 1451
considering several coupled-channel parameterizations developed   9234 1451
from n + 235,238U and 239Pu experimental data , several of which  9234 1451
were used in ENDF/B-VI evaluations.  The Harwell potential by     9234 1451
Madland and Young (Ma78), the Bruyeres-le-Chatel (BRC) potential  9234 1451
by Lagrange (Ha82), and a modified version of the BRC potential   9234 1451
by Arthur and Young (Yo88, Yo92a) were examined.  Isospin         9234 1451
corrections were applied to all the potentials to adapt them for  9234 1451
the various U isotopes.  Corrections from the measured to the     9234 1451
unmeasured cases were made in the deformation parameters b2 and   9234 1451
b4, using a simple model by D. Madland to calculate deformation   9234 1451
parameters for targets without experimental information from      9234 1451
deformations given in the extensive Nix-Moller mass analysis.     9234 1451
For the optical model potential, we chose to use an isospin       9234 1451
version of the BRC potential (Ha82), which was inferred from      9234 1451
Lagrange's results for individual nuclides.  The lowest three     9234 1451
members of the 1/2+ ground state rotational band were included    9234 1451
in the calculations, that is, the 3/2+ and 5/2+ states at Ex =    9234 1451
11 and 56 keV were coupled with the 1/2+ ground state.  All of    9234 1451
the potentials considered gave total and reaction cross sections  9234 1451
that were reasonably consistent, so the selection was based       9234 1451
mainly on the fact that the BRC potential gave better agreement   9234 1451
with fission cross sections for odd U isotopes (233,235U) at      9234 1451
lower energies.                                                   9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   B.  Reaction Theory Calculations                               9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The Hauser-Feshbach statistical calculations were performed    9234 1451
with the COMNUC (Du70) and GNASH (Yo92b) codes.  Both codes       9234 1451
include a double-humped fission barrier model, using uncoupled    9234 1451
oscillators for the barrier representation in GNASH and coupled   9234 1451
or uncoupled oscillators in COMNUC, as described by Arthur        9234 1451
(Ar82a).  The COMNUC calculations include the possibility of      9234 1451
width-fluctuation corrections and corrections for class II        9234 1451
fluctuations, which are needed at lower energies, whereas GNASH   9234 1451
provides the preequilibrium corrections that are required at      9234 1451
higher energies.  Accordingly, COMNUC was used in the             9234 1451
calculations below about 0.5 MeV, utilizing a non-resonant model  9234 1451
and including class II fluctuations, and the GNASH code was       9234 1451
employed at higher energies using two uncoupled oscillators in    9234 1451
the fission calculations.                                         9234 1451
   Each compound nucleus formed in the calculations is permitted  9234 1451
to decay through the fission channel, by neutron emission, and    9234 1451
by gamma-ray emission.  Neutron transmission coefficients for     9234 1451
the Hauser-Feshbach calculations are obtained from the coupled-   9234 1451
channel optical model.  Gamma ray transmission coefficients are   9234 1451
obtained from gamma-ray strength functions calculated with the    9234 1451
generalized Lorentzian model of Kopecky and Uhl (Ko90).           9234 1451
Transmission coefficients for fission are calculated from the     9234 1451
fission model summarized here and detailed in Yo92b.              9234 1451
   Gilbert and Cameron (Gi70) phenomenological level density      9234 1451
functions were used to represent continuum levels at ground-      9234 1451
state deformations, appropriately matched to available            9234 1451
experimental structure data at lower excitation energies.         9234 1451
Multiplicative factors were applied to the level density          9234 1451
functions to account for enhancements in the fission transition   9234 1451
state densities at the fission barriers due to increased          9234 1451
asymmetry conditions, and the continuum level densities were      9234 1451
matched to the discrete fission transition states at each         9234 1451
barrier.   The discrete fission transition state spectra were     9234 1451
calculated from bandhead information taken from calculations and  9234 1451
compilations by Britt (Br82).                                     9234 1451
   Initial values of fission barrier parameters were taken from   9234 1451
the work of Britt (Br82,Ba74), and we used default level density  9234 1451
parameters of Gilbert and Cameron for all ground state nuclei.    9234 1451
We only modified the Britt-Back parameters in very simple ways    9234 1451
in order to facilitate extrapolation of the parameters.  Our      9234 1451
modifications were limited to minor adjustments of the fission    9234 1451
barrier heights, the pairing energy at the fission barriers       9234 1451
(although we usually used the Gilbert-Cameron values), and the    9234 1451
level matching of the temperature region of the continuum level   9234 1451
densities at the fission saddles.  The barrier parameters for     9234 1451
238U were checked by calculating the fission probability for the  9234 1451
236U(t,pf)238U reaction, as was done by Arthur in an earlier      9234 1451
analysis (Ar82b).  Note that these calculations were performed    9234 1451
with COMNUC using a direct reaction (t,pf) spin distribution in   9234 1451
the analysis (Ar82c).                                             9234 1451
   We fit the experimental (n,f) and (n,g) cross sections for     9234 1451
all stable isotopes over the energy region of first-chance        9234 1451
fission using the COMNUC model code.  Experimental data exists    9234 1451
for targets of 232U, 233U, 234U, 235U, 236U, and 238U, which      9234 1451
allowed us to infer fission barrier parameters and gamma-ray      9234 1451
strength functions for the compound systems of 233U, 234U, 235U,  9234 1451
236U, 237U, and 239U.  Using the parameters determined from the   9234 1451
first-chance fission fitting without modification, we performed   9234 1451
GNASH calculations over the entire energy region of each target   9234 1451
nucleus.  We carried the calculations to 30 MeV, which involve    9234 1451
first-, second-, third-, fourth-, and fifth-chance fission        9234 1451
processes.   These comparisons provide a necessary test of the    9234 1451
reliability of our calculations, in that no adjustments are made  9234 1451
past the first-chance fission results.                            9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
III.  DESCRIPTION OF EVALUATED DATA BASE                          9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   A.  Total Cross Section                                        9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The evaluated total cross section below 10 keV is obtained     9234 1451
from the resonance parameter evaluation in ENDF/B-VI, with the    9234 1451
fission channel modified as described below.  From 10 keV to 30   9234 1451
MeV, the coupled-channel deformed optical model calculations      9234 1451
described above are used directly.                                9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   B.  Elastic Cross Section                                      9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The elastic cross section at all energies is obtained from     9234 1451
the difference of the total and nonelastic cross sections.        9234 1451
Below 10 keV it comes from the modified ENDF/B-VI resonance       9234 1451
parameters and at higher energies it is determined by the         9234 1451
coupled-channel optical model calculations.  Angular              9234 1451
distributions for elastic neutrons were obtained at all energies  9234 1451
from earlier (Yo94) coupled-channel calculations and are given    9234 1451
as Legendre expansions.                                           9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   C.  Fission Cross Section                                      9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The background present in the resolved resonance region        9234 1451
(below 102.5 eV) was lowered to improve agreement with a limit    9234 1451
given for the thermal fission cross section by Mughabghab         9234 1451
(Mu84).  At higher energies the fission cross section is based    9234 1451
on the theoretical analysis described above.                      9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   D.  Radiative Capture Cross Section                            9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   Below 10 keV, the capture cross section is based on the        9234 1451
ENDF/B-VI resonance parameters.  At higher energies the cross     9234 1451
section is calculated using the generalized Lorentzian model of   9234 1451
Ko90.  The normalization of the strength function was set by      9234 1451
requiring the calculated (n,g) cross section be consistent with   9234 1451
measured values for 235U.                                         9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   E.  Inelastic Neutron Cross Sections                           9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   Discrete (n,n') cross sections are included for the lowest 25  9234 1451
excited states of 237U.  The first and second excited states are  9234 1451
members of the K = 1/2 ground-state rotational band and include   9234 1451
coupled-channel as well as compound nucleus contributions.  The   9234 1451
remaining discrete-state cross sections through the 25th excited  9234 1451
state are based on compound nucleus calculations with             9234 1451
preequilibrium corrections with the GNASH code.  Angular          9234 1451
distributions for the discrete inelastic neutrons are taken from  9234 1451
the earlier [Yo94] analysis.                                      9234 1451
   The inelastic data corresponding to excitation energies in     9234 1451
237U above 0.54 MeV are given as energy-angle correlated          9234 1451
continuous spectra and were calculated with the GNASH code.  The  9234 1451
results are given in File 6 of the ENDF/B-formatted evaluation    9234 1451
(ENDF-6 format) and utilize systematics by Kalbach (Ka88) for     9234 1451
angular distribution information, parameterized in terms of       9234 1451
preequilibrium ratios calculated in GNASH.                        9234 1451
   The total inelastic neutron cross section from the present     9234 1451
analysis is drastically different from ENDF/B-VI in the energy    9234 1451
range below a few MeV.  Additionally, it should be pointed out    9234 1451
that the emission spectrum of inelastic neutrons is also          9234 1451
drastically different because it is dominated at lower energies   9234 1451
by direct reaction effects, which were apparently not included    9234 1451
in the ENDF/B-VI evaluation.                                      9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   F.  Cross Sections for 237U(n,xn) Reactions                    9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The 237U(n,2n), (n,3n), and (n,4n) cross sections result       9234 1451
entirely from the theoretical analysis and GNASH calculations.    9234 1451
The present analysis is somewhat similar to ENDF/B-VI below 12    9234 1451
MeV but is significantly different near 14 MeV.  The (n,3n) and   9234 1451
(n,4n) cross sections are also significantly different from       9234 1451
ENDF/B-VI near 14 MeV.                                            9234 1451
   Energy-angle correlated distributions are given for all the    9234 1451
237U(n,xn) reactions, making use of Kalbach's systematics (Ka88)  9234 1451
and the ENDF/B-6 File 6 representation.                           9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   G.  Nubar                                                      9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The evaluation of delayed and prompt nubar were carried over   9234 1451
directly from the ENDF/B-VI evaluation of 237U.  The prompt       9234 1451
nubar evaluation is based on the systematics of Manero and        9234 1451
Konshin (Ma72).                                                   9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   H.  Fission Neutron Spectra                                    9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The fission neutron spectra in the revised evaluation is also  9234 1451
carried over directly from the 237U evaluation in ENDF/B-VI.  A   9234 1451
maxwellian representation is used for the spectrum shape, with    9234 1451
energy-dependent temperature parameters based on systematics.     9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
IV.  CONCLUSIONS                                                  9234 1451
                                                                  9234 1451
   The new analysis of n + 237U nuclear data should provide a     9234 1451
much improved representation of most reactions over the incident  9234 1451
energy range 10 keV to 30 MeV.  The most significant and obvious  9234 1451
improvement is in the inelastic neutron cross sections, spectra,  9234 1451
and angular distributions in the energy range from threshold to   9234 1451
5 MeV.  The fission cross section was reevaluated using model     9234 1451
parameters consistent with neighboring U isotopes.  The new       9234 1451
analysis also should result in improved representations of the    9234 1451
(n,xn) cross sections, and certainly in the (n,xn) neutron        9234 1451
energy and angular distributions.                                 9234 1451
   This evaluation is regarded as preliminary until the results   9234 1451
of our assumptions regarding the fission cross section can be     9234 1451
assessed in integral calculations.  Additionally, improvements    9234 1451
to the evaluations of nubar and the fission neutron spectra       9234 1451
using the Madland-Nix approach will be considered in the future.  9234 1451
